V curtailment is equitably distributed\namong prosumers with a computational burden on par with conventional DOPF\napproaches. Moreover, different fairness methods result in different patterns\nof curtailment, which a regulator may choose between.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Mar 2022 16:15:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-10"}
{"id":"2203.04843","submitter":"Aurel Bulgac","authors":"Aurel Bulgac, Matthew Kafker and Ibrahim Abdurrahman","title":"Measures of complexity and entanglement in fermionic many-body systems","comments":"21 pages, 14 figures, published version","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. C 107, 044318 (2023)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevC.107.044318","report-no":"NT@UW-22-02","categories":"nucl-th cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  There is no unique and widely accepted definition of the complexity measure\n(CM) of a many-fermion wave function in the presence of interactions. The\nsimplest many-fermion wave function is a Slater determinant. In shell-model or\nconfiguration interaction (CI) and other related methods, the state is\nrepresented as a superposition of a large number of Slater determinants, which\nin case of CI calculations reaches about 20 billion terms. Although in practice\nthis number has been used as a CM for decades, it is ill defined: it is not\nunique, and it depends on the particular type and the number of single-particle\nwave functions used to construct the Slater determinants.\n  The canonical wave functions/natural orbitals and their corresponding\noccupation probabilities are intrinsic properties of any many-body wave\nfunction, irrespective of the representation, and they provide a unique\nsolution to characterize the CM. The non-negative orbital entanglement entropy,\nwhich vanishes for a Slater determinant, provides the simplest CM, while a more\ncomplete measure of complexity is the entanglement spectrum. We illustrate\nthese aspects in the case of a complex non-equilibrium time-dependent process,\ninduced nuclear fission described within a real-time Density Functional Theory\nframework extended to superfluid systems, which can describe simultaneously the\nlong-range and the short range correlations between fermions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Mar 2022 16:16:47 GMT"},{"version":