{"id":"2203.05343","submitter":"Alain J. Brizard","authors":"Alain J. Brizard","title":"Action-angle coordinates for motion in a straight magnetic field with\n  constant gradient","comments":"12 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.cnsns.2022.106652","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.plasm-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The motion of a charged particle in a straight magnetic field ${\\bf B} =\nB(y)\\,\\wh{\\sf z}$ with a constant perpendicular gradient is solved exactly in\nterms of elliptic functions and integrals. The motion can be decomposed in\nterms of a periodic motion along the $y$-axis and a drift motion along the\n$x$-axis. The periodic motion can be described as a particle trapped in a\nsymmetric quartic potential in $y$. The canonical transformation from the\ncanonical coordinates $(y,P_{y})$ to the action-angle coordinates $(J,\\theta)$\nis solved explicitly in terms of a generating function $S(\\theta,J)$ that is\nexpressed in terms of Jacobi elliptic functions. The presence of a weak\nconstant electric field ${\\bf E} = E_{0}\\,\\wh{\\sf y}$ introduces an asymmetric\ncomponent to the quartic potential, and the associated periodic motion is\nsolved perturbatively up to second order.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 10 Mar 2022 12:46:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-17"}
